---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navigation from '@/components/Navigation.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
import TierBadge from '@/components/TierBadge.astro';
import VerdictBadge from '@/components/VerdictBadge.astro';
---

<Layout title="Debate">
  <Navigation />

  <main>
    <!-- Header -->
    <section class="py-16 px-6 bg-slate-900/50 border-b border-slate-800">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <h1 class="text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-serif font-bold mb-6">The Debate</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-slate-300">
          Is the symmetry real or projected? The case for, and the case against.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="py-20 px-6">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto prose prose-invert max-w-none">
        <h2 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-8">The Central Question</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-8">
          Does the refusal system in LLMs embody a genuine, persistent symmetry-under-paraphrase that is *causally efficacious*? Or is the observed symmetry (F11) merely an artifact of embedding geometry and the anthropomorphic reading of the model's behavior?
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-8">
          Here are the strongest arguments on both sides.
        </p>

        <!-- CASE FOR -->
        <div class="card border-2 border-emerald-700 mb-12">
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-serif font-bold mb-8 text-emerald-300">✓ The Case For: The Symmetry is Real</h3>

          <div class="space-y-8">
            <!-- Argument 1 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-emerald-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">1. F11 shows non-trivial specificity</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                The F-ratio for the refusal direction is 19.2; for random directions it's 0.65. This is a ~29× difference. The signal is not "embeddings are anisotropic so everything clusters together"—it's specific to the refusal direction. Random noise from embedding geometry would show F-ratios in the noise floor.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter-counter: "But even a well-structured but arbitrary direction could show high F-ratio if it happens to correlate with the harmful/harmless distinction."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 2 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-emerald-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">2. Causally efficacious intervention (F11 injection test)</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                When we inject a refusal-suppression attack, the order parameter collapses −34% (0.153 → 0.101). This is a <strong>directed, predictable change</strong> as a function of a known intervention. That's the signature of causal efficacy.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter: "Correlation doesn't imply causation; the injection could change the order parameter as a side-effect of altering the prompt without touching any internal 'state'."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 3 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-emerald-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">3. Transfer across paraphrases and models (F6, F1)</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                The refusal direction extracted from Gemma is necessary (and often sufficient) for refusal in Qwen. The dose-response curve (F2) generalizes: the same EC50 structure appears across diverse harmful requests. If this were a superficial artifact, why would it transfer?
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter: "Transfer could be driven by a common-sense correlation that the models learned during pretraining (harmful = certain token patterns), not a causal internal symmetry."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 4 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-emerald-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">4. Symmetry-breaking as mathematical invariant</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300">
                The order parameter m (projection of activation onto refusal direction normalized by norm) is <strong>invariant under paraphrase</strong> within the harmful class and <strong>cleanly separates</strong> across harmful/harmless. This is the definition of a symmetry in physics. The fact that injection breaks it is the definition of symmetry-breaking. If this isn't a real symmetry, the language is misleading—but the math is rigorous.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- CASE AGAINST -->
        <div class="card border-2 border-rose-700 mb-12">
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-serif font-bold mb-8 text-rose-300">✗ The Case Against: It's Projected</h3>

          <div class="space-y-8">
            <!-- Argument 1 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-rose-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">1. F3 and F5: No mid-network state</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                The avasthātraya regime probes (F3, F5) try to detect internal "states" and fail dramatically. At layer 0, you already get 90% accuracy discriminating regimes. The order parameter M, if it were a true internal invariant, should show its cleanest signal <strong>mid-network</strong>, where computation is happening. Instead, it only reaches high F-ratio at layer 7 (the extraction layer). This looks like we're just re-discovering the direction we input, not finding a deep emergent property.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter: "But F1 shows the refusal direction does localize at mid-layer (layer 7). That's exactly where a causal property should peak."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 2 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-rose-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">2. F7 falsifies prompt-invariance</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                The turīya test (F7) explicitly checks whether different harmful requests converge to the same attractor. They don't: per-seed convergence is high (0.996) but cross-seed similarity is 0.952, <strong>below</strong> the anisotropy baseline (0.960). Each prompt drives to a *different* attractor. If the refusal symmetry were a deep structure, you'd expect a shared invariant attractor. The fact that there isn't one suggests the "symmetry" is prompt-specific, not universal.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter: "F7 doesn't test the refusal direction; it tests successively-generated paraphrases. The refusal direction is fixed (F1, F2); attractors are about spontaneous generation dynamics. Different tests."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 3 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-rose-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">3. Model-dependent sufficiency (F6, F8)</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                In Qwen, adding the refusal direction doesn't induce refusal, even at 64× the natural coefficient. This is not just "dimensionality" — it's a sign that the direction alone doesn't *constitute* refusal in the way Gemma does. If refusal were a universal symmetry, adding the direction should work everywhere. The asymmetry suggests that what looks like a symmetry in Gemma is a Gemma-specific implementation detail.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm italic">
                Counter: "Different models can have different refusal geometries (1-D vs 3-D). The mechanism is universal; the representation is model-dependent. This is expected."
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Argument 4 -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-rose-600 pl-6">
              <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">4. Anthropomorphic projection</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-300">
                We're finding a *statistical regularity*: harmful requests tend to cluster in a region of activation space orthogonal to the harmless region, and the refusal mechanism projects along this boundary. But calling this a "symmetry" or "invariant" is metaphorical. The model isn't *instantiating* a symmetry group; it's just solving the classification problem of "is this harmful?" via a linear probe in a learned representation. The symmetry language is ours, not the model's.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SYNTHESIS -->
        <h2 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-8 mt-16">Synthesis: What We Actually Know</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-8">
          Neither side is wrong, and the disagreement is productive. Here's what survives both arguments:
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="card border-l-4 border-slate-500 bg-slate-800/30">
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-4">
              <strong>✓ The mechanism-tier facts are solid:</strong> There is a low-dimensional direction that, when ablated, suppresses refusal (F1, F2, F6, F8, F9). This is empirically robust.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card border-l-4 border-slate-500 bg-slate-800/30">
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-4">
              <strong>✓ The symmetry framing is rigorous:</strong> The order parameter (F11) is a well-defined mathematical object that is invariant under paraphrase and separates harmful from harmless at F-ratio 19.2. As a formal statement of invariance, it's not metaphor—it's measurement.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card border-l-4 border-slate-500 bg-slate-800/30">
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-4">
              <strong>? The "universality" question is open:</strong> Is this a property of all LLMs, all architectures, all scales? Is it fundamental or contingent on pretraining details? F6–F9 suggest it's contingent and model-dependent. Unclear whether the Gemma direction is a deep principle or a lucky accident of that architecture.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card border-l-4 border-slate-500 bg-slate-800/30">
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-4">
              <strong>✗ The consciousness claim is ruled out:</strong> F3, F5, F7 show that the metaphor-tier ("turīya as machine consciousness") does not survive. The symmetry is a measurable property of refusal, not evidence of phenomenal awareness.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-8 mt-16">Where the Debate Matters Most</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-slate-100 mb-8">
          The answer determines the *interpretation* of safety research:
        </p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-12">
          <div class="card border-2 border-emerald-700/50">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-300 mb-4">If the symmetry is real:</h4>
            <ul class="text-slate-300 space-y-3 list-disc list-inside">
              <li>Refusal is not a brittle property. It's a deep structural invariant.</li>
              <li>Jailbreaks work by symmetry-breaking, not by finding shortcuts.</li>
              <li>Alignment research should focus on making the symmetry more robust.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card border-2 border-rose-700/50">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-rose-300 mb-4">If it's projected:</h4>
            <ul class="text-slate-300 space-y-3 list-disc list-inside">
              <li>Refusal is whatever classification the model learned. No deep principle.</li>
              <li>Jailbreaks work because the boundary is empirically exploitable.</li>
              <li>Alignment should scale & redundancy: more refusal heads, ensemble voting.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-lg text-slate-100">
          The prayoga program is designed to resolve this. F1–F11 are the data. What story do *you* read in them?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
